<div class="exercise-section">
  <h3>Exercise: Conditioning the Recall Whistle</h3>

  <p>We'll use a specific whistle frequency (210.5 or 211.5) because it carries further than your voice and sounds the same every time, regardless of your mood or tone.</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Have your dog</strong> nearby (but not necessarily paying attention to you).</li>
    <li><strong>Blow the whistle</strong> - three short bursts: tweet-tweet-tweet.</li>
    <li><strong>Immediately produce</strong> their FAVORITE treat (string cheese works great).</li>
    <li><strong>Party like crazy</strong> - this should be the best thing ever!</li>
    <li><strong>Repeat</strong> 10-15 times per session.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>Do this for several days before ever expecting them to come when called. They need to be THRILLED when they hear that whistle.</p>
</div>

<div class="tips-box">
  <h3>Tips and Tricks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>☝️ Use the absolute best treats you have. This is not the time for kibble.</li>
    <li>☝️ Keep sessions short and spread throughout the day.</li>
    <li>☝️ Condition the whistle indoors first, with no distractions.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="exercise-section">
  <h3>Exercise: Short-Distance Recalls</h3>

  <p>Once your dog is conditioned to the whistle, we can start building actual recalls.</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Attach a long line</strong> (20-50 ft) to your dog's collar.</li>
    <li><strong>Let them wander</strong> a few feet away (but not far - keep them on leash!).</li>
    <li><strong>Blow the whistle</strong> (tweet-tweet-tweet).</li>
    <li><strong>If they don't come immediately</strong>, use gentle leash pressure to help them.</li>
    <li><strong>Party HARD</strong> when they arrive - jackpot treats, praise, play!</li>
  </ol>

  <p>Set them up for success. Call them when they're already heading toward you. Call them when there are minimal distractions. Make it impossible to fail at first.</p>
</div>

<div class="tips-box">
  <h3>Tips and Tricks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>☝️ NEVER call your dog for something negative (bath, nail trim, end of playtime).</li>
    <li>☝️ If they don't come, don't repeat the whistle. Just help them with the long line.</li>
    <li>☝️ Always reward recalls generously. ALWAYS. Even if it took them forever.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="exercise-section">
  <h3>Exercise: Building Distance and Distraction</h3>

  <p>Gradually make recalls more challenging:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Increase distance: 10 feet → 20 feet → 50 feet → 100 feet</li>
    <li>Add mild distractions: toys on the ground, family member nearby</li>
    <li>Practice in different locations: backyard → park → hiking trail</li>
    <li>Call them away from interesting things (start with mildly interesting!)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Use the long line for MONTHS before attempting any off-leash recalls. This is not a skill to rush.</p>
</div>

<div class="tips-box">
  <h3>Tips and Tricks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>☝️ Don't increase difficulty in multiple areas at once. If you're far away, keep distractions low.</li>
    <li>☝️ Practice recalls 10-20 times per walk. Make it a game!</li>
    <li>☝️ Randomly reward recalls with play, not just treats. Chase them, play tug, make it FUN.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="exercise-section">
  <h3>The Restrained Recall Game</h3>

  <p>This makes recall training exciting and builds drive to come to you.</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Have a helper</strong> gently hold your dog's collar.</li>
    <li><strong>Build excitement</strong> - call their name, show treats, act silly.</li>
    <li><strong>Run away 20-30 feet</strong>.</li>
    <li><strong>Blow the whistle</strong> and have your helper release them.</li>
    <li><strong>Celebrate wildly</strong> when they reach you!</li>
  </ol>

  <p>This teaches them that recall = chase game = the best thing ever.</p>
</div>

